<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-integrating-to-get-solutions" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Integrating to solve <m>\frac{dy}{dx} = f(x)</m></title>

 <p>
    A simple but important special case of a first-order ODE is when the right-hand side does not involve the dependent variable. That is, the equation is in the form:
    <me>\frac{dy}{dx} = f(x).</me>
  </p>
<p>
  Let's explore this with the following example.
</p>

<example xml:id="ex-integrate-2x">
  <title>A Simple First-Order ODE</title>
  <p>
    Suppose <m>\frac{dy}{dx} = 2x</m>.  What does <m>y(x)</m> equal?
  </p>
  <hint>
    <p>
      Think about what operation undoes differentiation. What function has derivative equal to <m>2x</m>?
    </p>
  </hint>
  <solution>
    <p>
      Notice that <m>y(x) = x^2</m> is a solution since its derivative is <m>2x</m>. That is, we found an <em>antiderivative</em> of <m>2x</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Recall that adding any constant <m>C</m> gives the general antiderivative <m>y(x) = x^2 + C</m>, which is the general solution to <m>\frac{dy}{dx} = 2x</m>. So we simply took the indefinite integral of <m>2x</m>!
    </p>
  </solution>
</example>

<p>The graph with an interactive slider below demonstrates what is happening in this example.  </p>
<figure xml:id="fig-antiderivative-slider">
  <caption>
    Solutions to <m>\frac{dy}{dx} = 2x</m> of the form <m>y = x^2 + C</m>. As you drag the slider, notice that changing <m>C</m> shifts the curve vertically, but the tangent line at <m>x = 1</m> always has slope <m>2</m>, demonstrating that the derivative <m>\frac{dy}{dx} = 2x</m> is the same for every solution in the family!
  </caption>
  <interactive xml:id="interactive-antiderivative-slider" iframe="interactive-antiderivative-slider.html" width="80%" aspect="3:2">
    <static>
      <p>
        An interactive graph showing <m>y = x^2 + C</m> with a slider for <m>C</m> from <m>-5</m> to <m>5</m>. An amber dashed tangent line at <m>x = 1</m> moves up and down as <m>C</m> changes, but always has slope <m>2</m>, demonstrating that <m>\frac{dy}{dx} = 2x</m> is unchanged by <m>C</m>.
      </p>
    </static>
  </interactive>
</figure>


<p>
 Alright, well that turned out to be pretty easy once we understood
 what the differential equation was saying!
  We generalize this idea in the following observation. 
</p>

  <observation xml:id="obs-integrate-both-sides">
    <p>
      For a differential equation in the form
      <me>\frac{dy}{dx} = f(x),</me>
      the <term>general solution</term> is simply:
      <me>y(x) = \int f(x)\, dx + C.</me>
    </p>
  </observation>

 <p>
  Let's use this principle in the following examples. Try them on your own first!
</p>

<activity xml:id="act-integrating-odes">
  <title>Practice: Integrating to Find Solutions</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Try each of the following on your own before checking the solution. <alert>Try it on your own first!</alert>
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <task xml:id="task-integrate-3x2">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Solve <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx} = 3x^2</m> with initial condition <m>y(1) = 3</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        Integrating both sides:
        <me>y = \int 3x^2\, dx = x^3 + C.</me>
        Applying the initial condition <m>y(1) = 3</m>:
        <me>3 = 1^3 + C \implies C = 2.</me>
        So the specific solution is:
        <me>y(x) = x^3 + 2.</me>
        We can verify: <m>\frac{dy}{dx} = 3x^2</m> <m>\checkmark</m> and <m>y(1) = 1 + 2 = 3</m> <m>\checkmark</m>.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>

  <task xml:id="task-second-order-integrate">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Find the general solution to <m>\dfrac{d^2p}{dt^2} = 3</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <hint>
      <p>
        Notice the left-hand side involves a second derivative, which we can write as <m>\frac{d}{dt}\!\left(\frac{dp}{dt}\right) = 3</m>. Apply the same integration principle to get <m>\frac{dp}{dt} = \int 3\, dt</m>, then integrate again.
      </p>
    </hint>
    <solution>
      <p>
        Since <m>\frac{d^2p}{dt^2} = \frac{d}{dt}\!\left(\frac{dp}{dt}\right)</m>, we integrate twice.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>First integration:</alert> Starting from <m>p'(t) = \int 3\, dt</m>:
      </p>
      <solution>
        <title>Reveal</title>
        <p>
          <me>p'(t) = 3t + C_1.</me>
        </p>
      </solution>
      <p>
        Now that we have <m>p'(t) = 3t + C_1</m>, we integrate again.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Second integration:</alert> Starting from <m>p(t) = \int (3t + C_1)\, dt</m>:
      </p>
      <solution>
        <title>Reveal</title>
        <p>
          <me>p(t) = \frac{3}{2}t^2 + C_1 t + C_2.</me>
        </p>
      </solution>
     <p> You can verify that the general solution satisfies <m>p''(t) = 3</m>.
     </p>
    </solution>
  </task>

</activity>
<note xml:id="note-two-constants">
  <p>
   Notice in the last example we obtained two constants of integration <m>C_1</m> and <m>C_2</m> 
   from integrating twice. 
  </p>
</note>
<p>
  We now have a solid understanding of solving ODEs in the form <m>\frac{dy}{dx} = f(x)</m>. 
  Does this mean we've solved the entire course? Not quite, ODEs are rarely this simple! 
  The key feature of <m>\frac{dy}{dx} = f(x)</m> is that the right-hand side depends only 
  on the independent variable. In general, we won't be so lucky!

  Try the following checkpoint to determine when this method applies.
</p>
<exercise xml:id="ex-mc-integration-method">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Which of the following ODEs have been solved correctly using the integration method <m>y = \int f(x)\, dx + C</m>? Select all that apply.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <choices randomize="yes">
    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>\frac{dy}{dt} = e^t</m>, solved as <m>y = \int e^t\, dt = e^t + C</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct! The right-hand side depends only on <m>t</m>, so we can integrate directly. <m>\int e^t\, dt = e^t + C</m>.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>
    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>\frac{dy}{dx} = x^2 + 1</m>, solved as <m>y = \int (x^2 + 1)\, dx = \frac{x^3}{3} + x + C</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct! The right-hand side depends only on <m>x</m>, so we integrate directly to get <m>\frac{x^3}{3} + x + C</m>.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>
    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>\frac{dy}{dx} = 2y</m>, solved as <m>y = \int 2y\, dx = y^2 + C</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Incorrect! The right-hand side depends on <m>y</m>, not just <m>x</m>, so we cannot simply integrate both sides this way. We will learn how to solve ODEs like this later in the course!
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>
    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>\frac{dP}{dt} = tP</m>, solved as <m>P = \int tP\, dt = \frac{t^2}{2} P + C</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Incorrect! The right-hand side depends on both <m>t</m> and <m>P</m>, so direct integration doesn't work here. We will learn how to solve ODEs like this later in the course!
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>
  </choices>
</exercise>

